body: @pranav-prakash - how did you generate the faulty model? Apart from the one you pointed out there are other issues with this model too... While we should add more checks during model load to catch them... we need to fix the tool which generated this model too...

@askhade What other issues did you notice with the model? The missing link between `2799_Add_quant` and `Relu 2763` was the only one I could find, and with that fixed the model runs successfully.

I don't think this should be tagged as `quantization` because the model I supplied to the quantizer was not topologically sorted in the first place, which violates onnx spec. As for how I obtained that non-topologically sorted model, I think that was a bug in one of the pre-processing transformation scripts I had written.

I checked the model from model zoo and that is topologically sorted. Only onnx checker checks for topologically sorted nodes... ort does not... If you run onnx checker on Faulting_rcnn.onnx you will see the errors...
btw I added quantization label because it seemed to me that you were giving a valid onnx model to the quantizer tool and it was producing an invalid onnx model...

issue.title: QDQ Optimization for MaxPool does not check Opset Version

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
As @skottmckay ran into in #7042, loading the following model on latest ORT with optimizations enabled (in particular the QDQ fusion)

https://github.com/pranav-prakash/onnxruntime-riscv/releases/download/v0.01/FAULTING_rcnn.onnx

causes an opset error, since opset 10 does not support quantized input to `MaxPool`.

>[ONNXRuntimeError] : 10 : INVALID_GRAPH : This is an invalid model. Type Error: Type 'tensor(uint8)' of input parameter (7_quantized) of operator (MaxPool) in node (8) is invalid.

Because the model itself does not have a quantized input to the `MaxPool` node, I suspect that this is due to lack of opset check in the QDQ transforms

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/790fc11e6012c6591a258cea15c56c4c87685b54/onnxruntime/core/optimizer/qdq_transformer/qdq_simple_ops.cc

**Urgency**
None

**To Reproduce**
Model is attached above, run with optimizations enabled

**Expected Behavior**
In the case of opset < 12, QDQ fusion should not be performed on MaxPool. Additionally, perhaps a warning could be emitted (if VLOG is enabled).
